        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="left_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Militum Romanorum, et Macedonu[m] virtus, et copia. Ubi Virium, Ordinis, Loci Analysis. Nam cohortatio pertinet ad Ducu[m] 
                        officium: vt etia[m] peritissimus, potentissimusq[ue] vsus virium, ordinis, loci. Undè Imperator ferè, instar omnium. 
                        Sed tamen, vt fiat invictus, virtus etiam exercitus requiritur: et difficillimum erat Pyrrho, no[n] respondente exercitu, 
                        vincere Romanos: nec tam arduum Annibali, sufficiente exercitu: ut Alexandro facile, Persas, Indosq[ue] vincere, 
                        pra[e]cellente exercitu.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Alexander the Great"/>
                    <person name="Pyrrhus of Epirus"/>
                    <person name="Hannibal"/>
                    <location name="Rome"/>
                    <location name="Macedonia"/>
                    <location name="India"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The valour and resource of Roman and Macedonian soldiers. At the place where there is an analysis of strength, 
                order and place. For encouragement is part of the duty of leaders, just as well as the most skilled and powerful use of force, 
                order and place. From which [follows that] the commander is practically equal to all. 
                Yet to become invincible the valour of the army is also needed; and it was extremely difficult for Pyrrhus to defeat the Romans when the 
                army did not go along, and neither was it so hard for Hannibal when his army had sufficient capacity, just like it was easy for 
                Alexander to conquer the Indians with an army that was outstanding.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Ergo nec Locus, nec Ordo, nec Confidentia sufficiunt sine Viribus: et vana est sine Viribus Ira. Veruntamen ipsa[e] vires, 
                        non tam numero a[e]stimanda[e], quàm pondere: quomodò Alexander dicebat, Darium plures homines habuisse; se, plures milites. 
                        Et valet Vegetij regula: Amplius iuuat virtus, quàm multitudo: prouiso tamen, quod in eiusdem regulis excipitur; Amplius prodest 
                        Locus sa[e]pè, quàm virtus: et, Occasio in bello ampliùs solet iuvare, quàm Virtus: 
                        et in pra[e]lio amplius solet Fortuna potestatis habere, quàm Virtus. De Loco, et Occasione probo: de Fortuna dubito; 
                        qua[e] mihi pla[e]runq[ue] videtur effectus Virtutis: quomodò sua[e] quisq[ue] Fortuna[e] faber; et Virtus non serva, sed domina Fortuna[e].
                        Certè plura vincula fortiùs ligant: et, Cautela abundans non nocet: et Is demùm Invictus pra[e]lio, qui plurimum valet viribus, 
                        ordine, fiducia, Loco; nec ullum pra[e]termittit aptum Strategema, aut terribilem machinam.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Alexander the Great"/>
                    <person name="Darius III"/>
                    <person name="Vegetius"/>
                    <book title="De re Militari"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Therefore neither place, nor order, nor confidence suffice without fighting power, and without fighting power anger is empty. 
                The power itself, however, must not so much be weighed by its quantity, as by its substance. In the way that Alexander said that Darius 
                had more men, but that he himself had more soldiers. Also the rule of Vegetius is important: "valour is of more advantage than large numbers", 
                provided that one excludes from his rules: "Terrain is often of more advantage than valour", and "In war opportunity is usually of more advantage than valour", and 
                "In a battle fortune usually has more power than valour." I agree about terrain and opportunity, but am in doubt about fortune, 
                which to me mostly seems a consequence of valour, in the manner in which everyone is the craftsman of his own fortune, 
                and valour is not the servant but the mistress of fortune. Surely more bonds bind more strongly, and ample precaution does no harm. 
                And finally he is invincible who is most powerful by strength, order, faith, and place, and who does not overlook any fitting device or terrifying instrument.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
